    <section id="lab-challenges" class="py-20 bg-gray-50">
        <div class="container">
            <h2 class="section-heading">Lab Challenges</h2>

            <!-- Challenge 1 -->
            <div class="card">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-indigo-700 mb-3">Web Application SQL Injection</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Identify and exploit SQL injection vulnerabilities in a given web application to extract sensitive data from the database.</p>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Approach:</strong> Used manual testing techniques combined with automated tools to detect vulnerable parameters. Employed UNION-based and error-based SQL injection methods.</p>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Tools Used:</strong> Burp Suite, SQLMap, Firefox Developer Tools</p>
                <div class="mt-4 mb-4">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x300/e0e7ff/4f46e5?text=SQL+Injection+Screenshot" alt="SQL Injection Screenshot" class="rounded-lg shadow-md mx-auto">
                </div>
                <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Key Lessons Learned:</strong> Understanding the impact of improper input sanitization, the importance of parameterized queries, and effective use of proxies for web application testing.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Challenge 2 -->
            <div class="card">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-indigo-700 mb-3">Buffer Overflow Exploitation</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Exploit a vulnerable C program susceptible to buffer overflow to gain shell access.</p>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Approach:</strong> Analyzed the program's assembly code, identified the buffer, crafted a malicious payload including NOP sleds and shellcode, and overwrote the return address.</p>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Tools Used:</strong> GDB, Pwntools, NASM (for shellcode), Linux command line</p>
                <div class="mt-4 mb-4">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x300/e0e7ff/4f46e5?text=Buffer+Overflow+Screenshot" alt="Buffer Overflow Screenshot" class="rounded-lg shadow-md mx-auto">
                </div>
                <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Key Lessons Learned:</strong> Deep understanding of memory layout, stack frames, assembly language, and the intricacies of exploit development.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Challenge 3 -->
            <div class="card">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-indigo-700 mb-3">Network Packet Analysis</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Analyze a given PCAP file to identify malicious network activity, extract credentials, and reconstruct communication flows.</p>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Approach:</strong> Used Wireshark to filter traffic, follow TCP streams, and identify suspicious patterns. Applied various display filters to narrow down relevant packets.</p>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Tools Used:</strong> Wireshark, Tshark</p>
                <div class="mt-4 mb-4">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x300/e0e7ff/4f46e5?text=Packet+Analysis+Screenshot" alt="Packet Analysis Screenshot" class="rounded-lg shadow-md mx-auto">
                </div>
                <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Key Lessons Learned:</strong> Proficiency in network protocol analysis, identifying common attack signatures, and the importance of network forensics in incident response.</p>
            </div>

